metadata.name: Sketches of the Departure #79
metadata.description:
Just like "Greetings From Habitable Zones" this piece is influenced by 70s retro poster aesthetics, Impressionism (colors) and the infinite vastness of space.
The palette consists of 11 carefully chosen colors which can occur randomly in every part of the piece.

Features:
 - Newborn rate / cocoon count
 - Probability of arrival / fleet size
 - Propulsion type
 - Fuel consumption

///
Click for audio.
Press "s" in live view to save a png of your sketch.

The music was written and recorded on April 4th, 2020 on a Tascam 4-track tape recorder.

///
Created with p5.js

metadata.name: Breeding Grounds #55
metadata.description:
Social Networks.
Molecular Clouds.
Neuronal Circuitries.
Quantum Mechanical Structures.

Blurring Boundaries.
Infinite Self-Similarities.

Total.
Mess.

Perfect.
Order.

/////
Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about “Breeding Grounds” and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

Press 's' to save a .png with the current resolution (2000x3000).
If you want a file with higher resolution and/or without the “Painting Ground Textures” for printing please contact me via Twitter or Discord. 

/////
Created with p5.js

Twitter: @serminmin / @pxlshrd

metadata.name: Ghrian #198
metadata.description:
Dutch auction (13/11/9/6/3), with price decreasing every 10 minutes after the start of the auction until 9 tez. Price will then decrease to 6 tez after 2 hours, then to 3 after 12 hours.

A selection of 33 different palettes.

The brush draw is determined by angles, shapes, randomly chosen overdraws, brush sizes and widths, among other things.

- Left arrow = draw in 2125x1375
- Right arrow = draw in 11x17 landscape mode fit to screen height
- Up arrow = draw in 1375x2125
- Down arrow = draw in 11x17 portrait mode fit to screen width
- Enter = draw in full window
- Tab = draw in 1400x1400
- Shift = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides
- Alt = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides (default pixel density)
- Left mouse click = save as a png

Pixel density is set to 2 for all of the options above unless noted otherwise.

Please note that the drawing can take quite a while to run, especially in the full screen modes.

See thread below for additional details:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1492619586931413000?s=20&t=N8joIBuTNzYYjmcBex0QJQ

metadata.name: Soragna #445
metadata.description:
Soragna is an abstract generative series reproducing the effect of paint strokes.
The fundamental element of this system is an object composed of two lines which oscillate perpendicular to the direction of movement. A little like a bird flapping its wings, each element moves on the canvas, leaving behind it the imprint of its passage.

Variability of editions is ensured by:
- 18 color palettes (including 4 rare)
- possibility to combine 2 different palettes
- Constrained directions of the field
- Field symmetries
- Speed, size and size variability of "birds"


To save as a png file, press the following keys:
- [1] for a 2400x4000 pixel image
- [2] for a 4800x8000 pixel image
- [3] for a 7200x12000 pixel image

The image must be recalculated before the chosen dimension can be downloaded. The wait is worth it.



Note regarding the symbolism of the series:

I thought it was interesting to publish this series to celebrate the end of the fxhash beta. The artists on fxhash are like these birds leaving behind them the trace of their passage on the site. Their paths are sometimes parallel, they can cross and even sometimes come together to produce unique collaborations.

Thank you to all the artists and collectors for making the last few months an incredible journey! The best is still to come ...

Artist: Estienne
March 2022
License: NFT 2.0

metadata.name: Miniscapes #356
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: We Are Alone Together #414
metadata.description:
We meander through the flows of life, alone but together. This experience — an ultimately solitary one — is communicated but never truly shared. Our consciousnesses live in a perpetual separated state, alone but together.

############

Display resolution scales with window size. Press ’h’ (in live mode) to generate a 6000x7500 hi-res image. This may take a few seconds to generate depending on your hardware. Press ‘d’ to redraw the artwork.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: Sano #57
metadata.description:
Using Coronado’s algorithm as a starting point, Sano extends and embraces the notion of beauty existing in imperfection but allows for more impressionistic compositions with less structure, letting something atmospheric and understated emerge with subtle interactions that combine into dissonant chordal expressions infusing a breadth of emotion while maintaining a characteristic timbre.

Just as Coronado referenced a beat-up vintage guitar that had a patina and sound all its own, Sano refers to the vintage amp it was plugged into. A tube-amp from the 1960s with a spring reverb that when combined with single coils and hollow body of the guitar delivered screaming feedback as well as wonderfully gritty warm tones, which this algorithm attempts to echo visually.

There are 100 artist curated outputs in this short-form collection.

Keys:
S : save at current resolution
1 → 6 : save 2000x2500 → 12000x15000
(Chrome recommended for higher resolutions)

metadata.name: Hashed Cities #66
metadata.description:
This token generates a deterministic set of minimal, abstract buildings of varying widths, heights, transparencies, and patterns, assembling a skyline view of your own unique imaginary city. Each city comes with its own randomized city day.

Each mint has a native setting (Day or Night) which combined with the current time of viewing influences real-time movements of celestial bodies in your mint, e.g. on a mint with the Day setting, the sun will only appear when viewed during the day. The piece will re-render every minute.

The individual strokes of this token feature some of my latest developments of an algorithm that generatively simulates the texture of print imperfections. They are randomized at each render to give it a unique character. Note that depending on the complexity of each mint, some renders may introduce a brief pause. The aesthetics are greatly inspired by plotter art of early computer artists such as 'City Painting' by Grace C. Hertlein.

Made in p5js
Created Nov 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: {Lumina} #662
metadata.description:
The restitution of a breath
Your breath is your artwork

{Lumina} is part of the installation Σ Lumina taking place at Musée d’Orsay. A free live minting is scheduled from February 13th to March 10th, 2024. 

Breath, the vital essence, embodies our interconnection. It carries our shared heritage. A medium that helps Σ Lumina to unite the physical and the digital, the living with the coded. The voices of Orsay resonate within us, their breath becoming ours, landscaping our common creation.


Art curators of {Le Code d’Orsay}:
Christophe Leribault,
Président de l’Établissement public du musée d’Orsay et du musée de l’Orangerie
Virginie Donzeaud, Administratrice générale adjointe

16x16
HTML, js, Webgl
Location: Musée d’Orsay
